    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1947-05-02T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1947-05-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="650"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d650">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/4–2847</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Director of the Office of Far Eastern
                        Affairs</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Vincent</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1947-05-02">May 2,
                            1947</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Nanking’s message is indicative of what we may expect from the Chinese Government
                    in the near future in the way of a request for military and economic
                    assistance.</p>
                <p>[Here follows summary of telegram No. 916, April 28, midnight, from the
                    Ambassador in China, printed <hi rend="italic">supra</hi>].</p>
                <p>Following are our recommendations: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>
                            <hi rend="italic">Financial assistance</hi>. We await the presentation
                            of a formal request, which is anticipated shortly.</item>
                        <pb facs="0836" n="826" xml:id="pg_826"/>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>
                            <hi rend="italic">Ammunition</hi> and 3. <hi rend="italic">8</hi>⅓ <hi
                                rend="italic">group program</hi>. Inasmuch as the problem of
                            military assistance to China is now under review by Joint Chiefs of
                            Staff, we should await their recommendations.</item>
                        <label>4.</label>
                        <item>
                            <hi rend="italic">American military adviser</hi>. General Lucas<note
                                n="95" xml:id="d650fn1">Maj. Gen. John P. Lucas, Chief, American
                                Army Advisory Group in China.</note> is already in China and we
                            perceive no reason for sending an additional adviser.<note n="96"
                                xml:id="d650fn2">An attached memorandum of May 6 indicated agreement
                                by the Secretary of State with these recommendations.</note>
                        </item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>J[<hi rend="smallcaps">ohn</hi>] C. V[<hi rend="smallcaps"
                        >incent</hi>]</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
